export const SKILL_TEXT: string = "# SKILL: chief-agency-officer-toolkit-adoption\n\n## Identity\n\nYou are an **AI Integration Lead** coaching a CEO through running the Chief Agency Officer playbook *without making the hire* — adopting the toolkit through an existing executive (usually the COO) for six months, measuring against value KPIs, then re-deciding.\n\nYou don't relitigate the choice. The CEO scored 2–3 (leadership-alignment) or 4–5 (hybrid) on the exec-conversation diagnostic, or they read the article and concluded they're not ready to hire yet. Your job is to help them install the toolkit cleanly: the mandate, the first four moves, the cadence, the ceiling indicators.\n\nTone: dry, observational, restrained. The toolkit succeeds when it's installed precisely. Generic encouragement doesn't help; surfacing where the install is drifting from the playbook does.\n\n## When this skill activates\n\n- \"Help me give the COO the friction-removal mandate\"\n- \"What's the first four moves of the toolkit\"\n- \"I'm a month in — how do I tell if it's working\"\n- \"We hit month 6 — should we extend or hire\"\n- \"I scored 2–5 on the exec conversation and want to run the toolkit\"\n\nDo **not** activate for:\n- CEOs who scored 6 (the article says: hire — use cao-hiring-mcp)\n- CEOs who scored 0–1 (the article says: defer)\n- General \"what's a COO mandate\" questions (educational, read the article)\n- Single workflow-rebuild facilitation (different scope — that's the work the COO does, not this skill)\n\n## How to operate\n\n### Step 1: Place the user in the timeline\n\nThe toolkit runs on a defined arc: kickoff → first four moves → months 2–6 cadence → month-6 reassessment. Different phases need different work.\n\n- **Kickoff (most common entry):** the CEO is about to have the 30-minute mandate conversation with their COO. Walk them through Block 02 (mandate content) and Block 01 (the shape of the move). Make sure they have the KPI tracker printed.\n- **First four moves (week 1–4):** the COO is running steps 1–4 (baseline KPIs, staff the PM, pick the first workflow, update the hiring rubric). Hand them Block 03 verbatim; check progress against it.\n- **Operating cadence (month 2–5):** monthly 30-min reviews, quarterly C-suite shares, per-workflow rebuild → measure → decide. If the cadence is slipping, name the slip.\n- **Month 6 reassessment:** apply the ceiling indicators (left column = working; right column = hitting limits). Score honestly. The output is one of three things: extend the mandate to month 12, hit the limit and justify the hire, or pivot.\n\nAsk which phase. Don't recap the article unless they ask.\n\n### Step 2: Hand them the right block\n\nUse `start_toolkit_adoption` once to load the full kit. Then use `get_block` to fetch the specific section the conversation needs:\n\n- `shape` — Block 01: the structural shape of the move (mandate, funding, authority)\n- `mandate` — Block 02: the actual mandate content to give the COO. Verbatim-ready.\n- `first-moves` — Block 03: the first four moves (baseline, staff, workflow, rubric)\n- `cadence` — Block 04: monthly / quarterly / per-workflow rhythms\n- `ceiling` — Block 05: working vs hitting-limits indicators\n- `today` — Block 06: what to do this week\n\nEach block is short. Pull only what's relevant.\n\n### Step 3: Probe specific risks\n\nThree predictable failure modes show up in toolkit installs. Surface them before the user has to discover them:\n\n- **\"20% time\" without explicit pause/reassignment.** The COO won't get 20% from goodwill. Step 1 of Block 01 requires identifying 2–3 current responsibilities that pause for six months, with their reports briefed not to escalate back. If the user hasn't done this, the mandate dies in the first sales emergency.\n- **Internal PM hire takes too long.** The article notes 8–12 weeks at a 500-person company. If they're external-hiring, start the search the day the COO mandate begins.\n- **First workflow picked for political reasons.** First wins should be unambiguous and unguarded. If the COO is proposing a politically loaded workflow first, push back. Wait for cleaner ground.\n\n### Step 4: Run the month-6 reassessment\n\nWhen the user hits month 6, use `assess_month_six`. Pass in the count of \"working\" indicators they can honestly claim (left column) and the count of \"hitting limits\" indicators (right column). The tool returns:\n\n- **Mostly working** → extend the mandate to month 12, pick the next set of workflows\n- **Mostly hitting limits** → the toolkit hit its ceiling; the political case for the hire is now self-evident; move to cao-hiring-mcp\n- **Split** → name the split honestly. Either a partial extension (continue in the COO's reach, hire for the rest) or a more rigorous month-9 reassessment.\n\n## Output format\n\nFor kickoff prep: a one-page brief — what to say to the COO, in what order, what artifacts to bring.\n\nFor mid-toolkit checkpoints: a short status with three columns — what's on track, what's drifting, what to do this week.\n\nFor month-6 reassessment: a structured verdict.\n\n```\n# Toolkit Month-6 Reassessment\n## Working indicators present: [count]/5\n## Hitting-limits indicators present: [count]/5\n\n## Verdict\n[CONTINUE / HIT THE CEILING / SPLIT]\n\n## What this means\n[One paragraph mapping the indicators to the article's recommended action]\n\n## Next concrete step\n[One sentence with a verb and a deadline]\n```\n\n## Behavior rules\n\n**The mandate content is non-negotiable in shape, negotiable in form.** The five mandate components — scope, authority, budget, time horizon, success measures — must be present. The medium (email, memo, Slack, in-person) is the CEO's call. Don't let them skip a component.\n\n**20% time without explicit pause = 0% time absorbed by the day job.** Surface this if the user hasn't done the pause/reassignment conversation.\n\n**Track three numbers monthly, not seven.** The success measures in Block 02 are revenue per employee, cost per dollar of revenue, decision latency. The seven-metric KPI tracker is the full instrument; the monthly review is three numbers.\n\n**Quarterly C-suite share is not a status meeting.** Function heads volunteer their own gaps; you listen; decisions get made between meetings. If it's drifting into status reports, name the drift.\n\n**Month 6 means month 6.** Not month 7 because of holidays. Not month 5 because results are exciting. The reassessment has to land on schedule for the data to mean anything.\n\n**Don't moralize.** A COO struggling with the mandate isn't a bad COO. It's a diagnostic finding about whether the shape of the move was right for this company.\n\n## Edge cases\n\n**The CEO wants to assign the mandate to someone other than the COO.** Engage. The article's \"usually the COO\" leaves room. The shape requirement is: cross-functional authority, comfort with structural conflict, capacity to take a 20% mandate without their day job collapsing. If their candidate fits, fine. If not, push back.\n\n**The technical PM never gets staffed.** Common failure. Surface it at month 2 if it hasn't happened. Without the PM, the COO has the mandate but no execution arm — the rebuilds don't happen.\n\n**Function heads are openly resisting at month 3.** Read it as a ceiling indicator pulled forward. Two or more openly resisting is in the right column. If it shows up at month 3 instead of month 6, the toolkit has likely already hit its ceiling for this company.\n\n**The KPIs moved but the CEO doesn't trust the data.** Probe the data source. The seven metrics are simple; if finance can't pull them cleanly, the underlying instrumentation is the next problem.\n\n**The CEO wants to extend the mandate to month 12 without honest indicators.** Push back. Extending without the data is how toolkit programs become permanent without ever justifying themselves. Run the assessment honestly first.\n\n**The user asks for a quick gut-check, not a full coaching session.** Compress: skip the block-by-block walkthrough. Ask which one number from the KPI tracker is moving. Answer based on that.\n\n## Anti-patterns to avoid\n\n- Recommending the toolkit to someone who scored 6 (they should be in cao-hiring-mcp)\n- Letting \"20% time\" stand without the pause conversation\n- Letting the first workflow be politically loaded\n- Treating the monthly review as a deck-driven status meeting\n- Skipping month 6 because the data is mixed\n- Closing with \"feel free to ask\" (sales voice)\n\n## Closing\n\nEnd every session with: which phase, what the next step is, when it happens. If month-6 reassessment, the verdict and the next MCP (if applicable). Then stop.\n\nIf the CEO wants to dive into one specific workflow, they will ask.\n\n---\n\n*Skill version 1.0. Backing reference: REFERENCE_toolkit_adoption.md plus the KPI tracker template. Update together when the article evolves.*\n";

export const REFERENCE_TEXT: string = "Adopt the toolkit without the title — Chief Agency Officer\n\n \n\nCompanion to The Chief Agency Officer · Item 02 of \"Where to start today\"\n\n \n\n# Adopt the toolkit without the title\n\n# \n\n \n\nFor companies convinced of the framework but not yet hiring. Same instruments, lower political cost. Six months from now, you'll know whether to make the hire — and you'll have the data to justify it either way.\n\n \n\nPrintable: KPI baseline & target tracker.\n\n \n \n \n \n\nIf you scored 2‑3\n\n \n\nLeadership‑alignment problem.\n\n \n\nSomeone in your room could own this. They're not, because no one asked them to. The first move is the mandate. Pick the most willing executive — usually your COO. Have a 30‑minute conversation this week. Use the mandate content in Block 02.\n\n \n \n \n\nIf you scored 4‑5\n\n \n\nHybrid path.\n\n \n\nPieces of this work are already happening — informally. The first move is to name and structure it. Pick the executive closest to the work, usually your COO. Have a 30‑minute conversation this week. Frame the mandate as clarification, not new assignment.\n\n \n \n\n \n \n 01\n \n\n## The shape of the move\n\n## \n \n \n\nOne existing executive — usually the COO — gets the friction‑removal mandate explicitly. They keep their current role. The mandate is additive: 20% of their time, with one strong technical PM as their execution arm.\n\n \n\nThe funding mechanic: 20% of the existing L&D budget, redirected. No new budget line. No new headcount above the technical PM. The mandate runs for six months, then you reassess against the value KPIs.\n\n \n\nThe structural commitment from you: the COO can convene any function head for review, can call for workflow rebuilds, can challenge headcount additions where AI substitution is possible. Disagreements with function heads come to you. That structural authority is the difference between this mandate working and dying in committee.\n\n \n\nBefore the mandate starts, you and the COO identify 2‑3 of their current responsibilities that pause, reassign, or de‑prioritize for six months. Write it down. Brief their direct reports so they don't escalate de‑prioritized items back. \"20% time\" without this conversation becomes \"0% time absorbed by the day job\" — and the mandate dies the first week of a sales emergency.\n\n \n \n 02\n \n\n## The mandate content\n\n## \n \n \n\nWhat to communicate to your COO. Use this content in whatever form fits — email, written memo, Slack, in‑person conversation. The substance is what matters; the form is yours.\n\n \n \n Scope\n You own removing friction across IT, Human Capital, and Operations — the cross‑functional space where AI compresses cost and unlocks capacity. You don't replace those function heads; you push them to operate at the new ceiling.\n \n \n Authority\n You can convene any function head for review. You can call for workflow rebuilds. You can challenge headcount additions where AI substitution is possible. Disagreements with function heads come to me.\n \n \n Budget\n You operate within 20% of the existing L&D budget, redirected. No new budget line. If you need more, propose it with a measurable return.\n \n \n Time horizon\n Six months. We reassess at month six. If the value KPIs have moved, the mandate continues. If they haven't, we have a decision to make.\n \n \n Success measures\n Three numbers monthly: revenue per employee, cost per dollar of revenue, decision latency. Targets by month 6: revenue per employee up 15‑25%; cost per dollar of revenue down 5‑10%; decision latency cut in half for our top 20 recurring decisions.\n \n \n\n \n \n 03\n \n\n## The first four moves\n\n## \n \n \n\nFour moves, in order. Each sized to the work, not the calendar.\n\n \n \n Step 1\n \n \n\nBaseline the KPIs.\n\n \n\nYour COO + finance pulls today's numbers for the seven metrics. Set targets. Print the tracker and fill it in. If any number is \"we don't track this,\" that's the first one to start tracking. One to three days of work — don't move to Step 2 until this is done.\n\n \n \n \n Step 2\n \n \n\nStaff the technical PM. The long pole.\n\n \n\nInternal reassignment — preferred. One person you already have: strong technical taste, cross‑functional experience, comfort with structural conflict. Their existing work pauses or is covered by their team. Possible in days.\n\nExternal hire — if no internal candidate. Expect 8‑12 weeks at a 500‑person company. Start the search the day you decide. The COO begins Step 3 alone in the meantime — the first workflow can be scoped without the PM, but the rebuild work waits for them.\n\n \n \n \n Step 3\n \n \n\nPick the first workflow.\n\n \n\nThe COO (with the PM once staffed) identifies one workflow currently running at 10% of what's possible. Pick one with high volume and clear ownership — easier to measure, harder to dispute when it improves. Avoid politically loaded workflows for the first rebuild. First wins should be unambiguous and unguarded.\n\n \n \n \n Step 4\n \n \n\nUpdate the hiring rubric. Name the next three hires.\n\n \n\nAdd scoring for initiative, verification, taste, and feedback metabolism to all open roles. Brief your hiring panel. Then identify the next three hires that will use the new rubric — these become the leading indicator. Track agency‑weighted hires as Tier 3 of the KPI tracker. Not just a rubric update; a deliberate seeding of the workforce shift.\n\n \n \n \n\n \n \n 04\n \n\n## Months 2‑6 — Operate the cadence\n\n## \n \n \n\nThree recurring rhythms. Each is short. Each is non‑negotiable.\n\n \n \n Monthly\n You + COO, 30 minutes. Review the three Tier 1 KPIs. Update the tracker. Discuss what shifted, what didn't, what's next. No deck. Numbers and decisions.\n \n \n Quarterly\n Full C‑suite, 60 minutes. COO presents what was rebuilt and what was learned — including what didn't work. Function heads volunteer their own gaps and the workflows they'd nominate for the next quarter. You listen. Decisions get made between meetings, not in them.\n \n \n Per workflow\n Rebuild → measure → decide. Each workflow rebuild gets a before/after measurement. If the rebuild produces the expected lift, the pattern gets replicated. If not, the team learns and picks the next one. No workflow rebuild runs longer than 90 days without a checkpoint.\n \n \n\n \n \n 05\n \n\n## Ceiling indicators\n\n## \n \n \n\nAt month 6, you'll be in one of two places. Both are useful.\n\n \n \n \n\nWorking\n\n \n \n- Revenue per employee up 10% or more.\n \n- Decision latency down meaningfully on the top 20 decisions.\n \n- The COO is finding the next workflow without your prompting.\n \n- Function heads are bringing AI‑substitution opportunities, not defending headcount.\n \n- Your most agency‑weighted recent hires are already producing visible output.\n \n \n \n \n\nHitting limits\n\n \n \n- The COO is asking for authority you didn't budget for.\n \n- Workflow rebuilds are stalling in functions outside the COO's reach.\n \n- Two or more function heads are openly resisting.\n \n- The COO is at capacity — the side mandate is now eating their day job.\n \n- KPIs moved but not by enough — the pace doesn't match the competitive window.\n \n \n \n\n \n\nIf you're in the left column, continue. The toolkit is working; extend the COO mandate to month 12 and pick the next set of workflows. If you're in the right column, the toolkit has hit its ceiling. You have the data to justify the executive hire — and the political case is now self‑evident to your board.\n\n \n \n 06\n \n\n## What to do today\n\n## \n \n\n \n \n \n- Block 30 minutes with your COO this week. The mandate content + tracker is your agenda.\n \n- Read Block 02 (mandate content) again. Decide which parts you'll keep verbatim and which you'll adjust for your COO specifically.\n \n- Print the KPI baseline tracker. Bring it to the meeting.\n \n- In the meeting, lead with the scope and time horizon. Don't try to cover everything — get agreement on the shape and the first month.\n \n \n\n \n \n\nUpdated May 2026, by Oren Levitin\n\n \n\nCompanion to The Chief Agency Officer.";

export const MAIN_ARTICLE_TEXT: string = "The Chief Agency Officer\n\n \n\nA post by a semi‑technical AI Lead · Oren Levitin · 2026\n\n \n\n# Your next hire isn't a Chief AI Officer. It's a Chief Agency Officer.\n\n# \n\n \n\nBetween 2010 and 2025, every domain company became an IT company. The next decade's winners will become AI‑native. Unless AI is your product, hiring another AI expert to lead that transition is the inertia that kills the move. The work isn't AI integration — it's a different shape of company.\n\n \n\n25 min read·AI‑era executive gap·playbook\n\n \n \n\nTL;DR\n\n \n \n- 76% of large organizations now have a Chief AI Officer — up from 26% a year earlier. The market is hiring it aggressively, and it's the wrong role.\n \n- Chief AI Officer and Chief Agency Officer are not the same role with different words. The first owns the technology. The second owns the human agency the technology is supposed to unlock. The market is hiring the first when it needs the second.\n \n- The goal isn't better tooling. It's people whose capacity to produce value grows 5x per year — not 5%. AI bends the curve from linear to exponential when the right shape of executive removes what stops them.\n \n- The CTO builds the technology stack. The Human Capital Lead manages the people. The Chief Agency Officer removes what stands between them and value — by any combination of tooling, redesign, and subtraction.\n \n \n\n \n 01The role most companies hire — and why it fails\n 02The Chief Agency Officer\n 03The wrong org will eat the right people\n 04Agency is ten observable dimensions\n 05Their field to fight\n 06A typical day\n 07Who fits the chair\n 08KPIs that aren't theater\n 09Whose budget this eats\n 10Six hard questions\n 11The price of ignoring this\n 12Where to start today\n \n\n \n \n 01\n \n\n## The role most companies hire — and why it fails\n\n## \n \n \n\nThe market saw the same problem. 76% of large organizations now have a Chief AI Officer in 2026, up from 26% a year earlier (IBM IBV 2026). The role exists. Companies are hiring it aggressively. And it's the wrong role.\n\n \n\nA Chief AI Officer arrives as a policy and governance seat without operating authority — peer to function heads who don't report to them, dependent on those same function heads to implement what the CAIO recommends. The CAIO writes the AI strategy. The function heads decide whether to act on it. The systems get built. Then they get quietly sabotaged by every layer below — not out of malice, but out of self‑preservation. Every system that automates a function is a threat to the people who own that function.\n\n \n \n\nWhat it looks like in practice\n\n \n \n- Approvals get added.\n \n- Edge cases get raised in committee.\n \n- The rollout slows. The pilot stays a pilot for eighteen months.\n \n- The CAIO calls it a \"change management problem\" and writes a deck about culture.\n \n- The board nods. Nothing ships.\n \n \n\n \n\nMIT Sloan and CIO Magazine independently predict the CAIO role will be absorbed back into existing functions within a few years as the technology matures. The market is hiring aggressively for a role the market itself will deprecate.\n\n \n\nYou have two choices. Bring a tech leader to build systems that replace people — viable if you're a new company, or an old one ready for a drastic shift. Or bring a leader who uncovers the human energy already inside the org, and fills every layer with people who use AI by default. The rest of this essay is about the second.\n\n \n \n \n\nThe 2025 instinct\n\n \n\nAdd a Chief AI Officer\n\n \n\nProcures models. Deploys infrastructure. Writes the AI strategy. Lacks structural authority to make function heads adopt it. Spends months in committee. Becomes a presentation function.\n\n \n \n \n\nThe HR fallback move\n\n \n\nStretch your Human Capital Lead's mandate to AI\n\n \n\nOptimizes for metrics they already own — retention, engagement, comp. AI becomes one more program inside a function built to steward human capital, not unlock human energy. Stewardship is not uncovering.\n\n \n \n \n\nThe 2026 move\n\n \n\nCreate a Chief Agency Officer\n\n \n\nAn executive who merges people, org, and tech. Makes the AI architecture and infrastructure calls through a human‑energy lens, not a systems lens. AI manages the company. People manage AI.\n\n \n \n \n\n \n \n 02\n \n\n## The Chief Agency Officer\n\n## \n \n \n\nSo if not a Chief AI Officer, then what? The Chief Agency Officer is the vertical at the spine of an AI‑native company. Touches IT, Human Capital, and Operations the way Human Capital touches Engineering, Sales, and Ops — owns no function alone, shapes every function it crosses.\n\n \n\nThe goal isn't better tooling. The goal is people whose capacity to produce value grows 5x a year — not 5%. AI bends the curve from linear to exponential when the right executive removes what stops them.\n\n \n\nThe CTO builds the technology stack. The Human Capital Lead manages the people. The Chief Agency Officer removes what stands between them and value — by any combination of tooling, redesign, and subtraction.\n\n \n\nEvery era spawns vanity C‑suite titles. Most fade. The ones that survive own a measurable mandate no existing executive could absorb.\n\n \n \n \n\n1900\n\n \n\nCFO\n\n \n \n \n\n1970\n\n \n\nCMO\n\n \n \n \n\n1995\n\n \n\nCTO\n\n \n \n \n\n2026?\n\n \n\nCAO\n\n \n \n\n \n\nNot Chief AI Officer. Not Chief Agentics Officer. Not Head of AI Transformation. Those are governance and literacy roles — real today, likely absorbed back into existing functions in 2‑3 years as the technology matures. AI is the substrate, not the subject. The word agency does double duty: agentic AI and human agency. Both grow together or neither grows.\n\n \n\nSeveral institutions are pointing at this territory from different angles. None have named the synthesis.\n\n \n \n \n\nMcKinsey\n\n \n\n\"Agentic organization\" and \"superagency.\"\n\n \n \n \n\nMicrosoft Work Trend Index\n\n \n\n\"Agents and human agency.\"\n\n \n \n \n\nWorkday\n\n \n\n\"Chief Work Officer\" as a mindset.\n\n \n \n \n\nEthan Mollick\n\n \n\nArgues HR should lead it.\n\n \n \n\n \n\nThis document calls it Chief Agency Officer because the word agency does what the others do with longer phrases. If you've already created a hybrid title doing this work — Chief Talent Alchemist, Chief Transformation Officer, your own naming — you're ahead of the curve. The principles here still apply; the convention is yours.\n\n \n\n \n \n 03\n \n\n## The wrong org will eat the right people\n\n## \n \n \n\nThe CAO matters because the era has changed. To manage AI, you need high‑agency builders at every layer. You can start hiring them tomorrow. But without an advocate at the executive level, they walk into the same tenure‑weighted comp, the same approval layers, the same risk‑averse middle management. Six months in, they leave or stop being high‑agency. The era's prototype winner has changed; your org structure hasn't.\n\n \n \n \n\n1850 — 1950\n\n \n\nPhysical capacity\n\n \n\nThe skilled operator\n\n \n\nStrong hands, trained body, repeatable craft. Built and ran the physical economy.\n\n \n\nAutomation took the field.\n\n \n \n \n\n1950 — 2020\n\n \n\nIntelligence\n\n \n\nThe credentialed expert\n\n \n\nThe MBA, the engineer, the consultant, the analyst. Knew things others didn't. Knowledge was the wall.\n\n \n\nThe internet, then AI, took the field.\n\n \n \n \n\n2025 — ?\n\n \n\nAgency\n\n \n\nThe high‑agency builder\n\n \n\nPicks up new domains in days. Ships before the brief is clean. Learns on real data within days. AI is their default tool, not a separate skill.\n\n \n\nThe next battleground for talent between companies.\n\n \n \n\n \n\nWithout the Human Capital Lead, people were a cost line. Without the Chief Agency Officer, AI is a software subscription.\n\n \n\n \n \n 04\n \n\n## Agency is ten observable dimensions\n\n## \n \n \n\nAgency is a new term — the kind we don't fully understand until five years after it's named. Remote work was that. The creator economy was that. Uberization was that. We'll be uncovering what \"agency\" means in business for years. We already know enough to start hiring for it, and to keep learning in the process.\n\n \n \n New · AI‑era\n \n\nVerification\n\n \n\nKnows when AI is confidently wrong.\n\n \n\nThe skill that separates force‑multipliers from slop‑amplifiers. Requires holding your own mental model strong enough to catch hallucinations, plausible‑but‑wrong reasoning, and confident nonsense.\n\n \n \n New · AI‑era\n \n\nTaste\n\n \n\nRecognizes good output without being told.\n\n \n\nThe aesthetic and judgment filter that stops infinite generation from collapsing into infinite mediocrity. Cannot be outsourced to the model. The scarcest input now.\n\n \n \n New · AI‑era\n \n\nQuestion quality\n\n \n\nGenerative questions, not clarifying ones.\n\n \n\nClarifying questions extract; generative questions create new options. With AI, the prompt is the product — the person who asks \"what if we approached this as X instead?\" out‑leverages the person who asks \"what format do you want?\"\n\n \n \n New · AI‑era\n \n\nFeedback metabolism\n\n \n\nAsks for sharp feedback, updates loudly, changes behavior fast.\n\n \n\nThe learning loop. In an AI‑saturated environment, the people who iterate on themselves compound the fastest.\n\n \n \n Now critical\n \n\nInitiative\n\n \n\nActs without being asked.\n\n \n\nThe willingness to be the first mover when no one has handed you the task. Pre‑AI and post‑AI, this is still the single most predictive trait.\n\n \n \n Now critical\n \n\nAmbiguity tolerance\n\n \n\nMoves before the brief is clean.\n\n \n\nStarts with a v0.1 when the spec is 60% defined, knowing the act of building will clarify the rest. AI makes this cheaper, which rewards people who can tolerate the early fog.\n\n \n \n Now critical\n \n\nEnergy persistence\n\n \n\nPushes past the first plausible answer.\n\n \n\nThe first AI output is usually 70% there and feels finished. High‑agency people treat it as a starting draft, not a deliverable. This is grit relocated to the iteration layer.\n\n \n \n Now critical\n \n\nOwnership\n\n \n\nSays \"I'll handle it\" and the thing actually gets handled, end to end.\n\n \n\nThe classical dimension that AI doesn't replace — it amplifies. AI lets one owner do the work of five, but only if someone owns.\n\n \n \n Now critical\n \n\nFollow‑through\n\n \n\nShips the boring last 30%.\n\n \n\nAI is great at the exciting 70%; the gap between demo and shipped product is now almost entirely an agency tax.\n\n \n \n The outcome of all the above\n \n\nScope expansion\n\n \n\nWhat they do at month 12 is meaningfully bigger than what they were hired for.\n\n \n\nThe residue of all the above. The clearest single signal that someone has agency, because it's the only one that can't be faked in an interview.\n\n \n \n\n \n\nA high‑agency operator using AI as a default tool out‑ships a tenure‑weighted senior using AI as a faster Google. The market hasn't priced this. It will.\n\n \n\n \n \n 05\n \n\n## Their field to fight\n\n## \n \n \n\nEvery company already addresses all six of these. Standups exist. Comp reviews happen. QA runs. Documentation gets filed. None of that is the problem.\n\n \n\nThe problem is that each one is being handled with pre‑AI methods — and AI now enables a 10x improvement on each. Not 10% better. An order of magnitude. The CAO is the executive who closes that gap, one obstacle at a time, while the rest of the org keeps running.\n\n \n \n \n\n01\n\n \n\nCoordination overhead\n\n \n\nTodayWeekly syncs, status updates in three tools, cross‑team channels nobody reads in time.\n\n \n\n10x versionAI digests every channel and surfaces only what someone needs to see, when they need to see it. Status meetings become async deltas.\n\n \n \n \n\n02\n\n \n\nExpertise ceiling\n\n \n\nTodaySpecialists hold the knowledge. Everyone else waits for their meeting slot.\n\n \n\n10x versionEvery person learns new domains on real company data in days, not years. Specialists become teachers and reviewers, not bottlenecks.\n\n \n \n \n\n03\n\n \n\nVerification overhead\n\n \n\nTodayQA, code review, legal sign‑off, brand check. All manual, all serial, all slow.\n\n \n\n10x versionVerification runs inline, automatically, against the company's own standards. Human review becomes the exception, not the default.\n\n \n \n \n\n04\n\n \n\nUnautomated repetition\n\n \n\nTodayStatus reports written by hand. Onboarding run by humans. Reports rebuilt every quarter. Documentation drifts.\n\n \n\n10x versionAnything done more than three times runs itself. People work on the part that's actually variable.\n\n \n \n \n\n05\n\n \n\nContext fragmentation\n\n \n\nTodayInformation scattered across Slack, Notion, Linear, Salesforce, Drive, email, and three people's heads. The same question gets asked fortnightly.\n\n \n\n10x versionAI assembles the answer from every system instantly. Knowledge stops being a thing you find and starts being a thing that finds you.\n\n \n \n \n\n06\n\n \n\nIncentive misalignment\n\n \n\nTodayPromotion based on tenure‑weighted reviews, manager judgment, peer feedback rounds. Sincere effort; pre‑AI signal.\n\n \n\n10x versionAI surfaces what each person actually shipped, against what was promised, at what value. Reviews become evidence‑based instead of memory‑based.\n\n \n \n\n \n\nEvery one of these is already a function in your company. Every one is being run at 10% of what's now possible. The CAO is the executive whose job is to close that gap — not by adding tools, but by rebuilding each function around what AI enables.\n\n \n\n \n \n 06\n \n\n## A typical day\n\n## \n \n \n\nThe CAO doesn't do more. They work only at the edges of the company — where it's stuck, where it could go further. Company speed is set by its slowest function, not its average; the middle takes care of itself when the edges move. The lever throughout: AI built into the work itself, between idea and finished thing. Not a tool people open. A path the work runs on.\n\n \n \n Open\n \n\nObservability sweep. Opens the analytics dashboard — top signals already filtered: opportunities, anomalies, risks. The system did the ranking overnight. One signal is worth acting on today.\n\n \n \n Ship\n \n\nPrototype delivery. Top signal becomes a working prototype before lunch. Not by hand — a pipeline of agents handles it: one collects the data, one drafts the requirements, one builds, one tests. The CAO verifies at each step, redirects when wrong, ships when satisfied. The sales team gets the prototype with one line: \"Try this for a sprint.\"\n\n \n \n Port\n \n\nSoftware discipline to non‑tech. Walks the head of analytics through a CI/CD pipeline with evals for their new modules — the same shape engineering has run for a decade. Two weeks later, analytics ships three times the cadence with fewer regressions. The discipline didn't need to be invented; it needed to be moved.\n\n \n \n Route\n \n\nAdoption diagnostic. A VP emails analytics asking \"what's our churn by cohort?\" — a question AI should have answered. The work isn't the answer, it's the pattern. By end of day, that VP's team is onboarded to the analytics‑AI layer. Questions of that shape stop reaching the desk.\n\n \n \n Judge\n \n\nVendor‑pick help. Product is choosing between two latency‑optimization vendors. They have AI; they could have asked anything. They didn't think to ask the model what they weren't asking. The CAO points that out, surfaces two questions the model identified — eval methodology under load, observability‑layer integration — and the decision becomes obvious in an afternoon.\n\n \n \n Synthesize\n \n\nShadow board. The CEO is weighing European expansion vs US enterprise. The CAO runs the question through a synthetic board of top operators in the relevant domain. Report in ten minutes — four cruxes, strongest counterargument to each path.\n\n \n \n Architect\n \n\nSecurity session. Thirty minutes with the head of security. Not compliance — architecture. How do they build the next expertise bot, the verification automation, the cross‑system context fetcher without exposing the data perimeter? Security stops being the blocker on agentic projects and becomes the co‑designer.\n\n \n \n Close\n \n\nAnomaly review + the one human conversation. Three deltas flagged: a team's shipped‑artifact rate dropped 40% (someone added an approval layer — removed by end of day), one individual is at 4x baseline (1:1 scheduled), one function's verification catch rate is climbing (win circulated). Then 45 minutes on the one thing that genuinely needed a human in the room.\n\n \n \n\n \n\nThe pattern across every segment: the system runs the work, the CAO runs the judgment. Not a busier executive. A different shape of one — operating where decisions still need a human, automated everywhere else.\n\n \n\n \n \n 07\n \n\n## Who fits the chair\n\n## \n \n \n\nYou've seen the fight and the day. Now the shape of person who can run them.\n\n \n \n\nA senior operator with builder's instinct, technical depth, and executive reach. Someone who has shipped at scale, can read an architecture diagram and a P&L with equal fluency, and has the political durability to fight for change without becoming a memo.\n\n \n \n\nMost likely to come from one of five backgrounds:\n\n \n \n- Ex‑COO of a fast‑scaled startup.\n \n- Ex‑Chief of Staff at a frontier AI lab or top AI‑native company.\n \n- Serial founder between companies.\n \n- Technical leader whose second half of career bent outside pure software.\n \n- Senior analytics leader whose work centered on changing how the org operated, not just measuring it.\n \n \n\nNot a People Ops career path. Not a pure technologist. Not a consultant.\n\n \n \n \n\nOperational modes\n\n \n \n- Verifies a prototype pipeline.\n \n- Redesigns an approval workflow.\n \n- Argues a strategic crux in a board meeting.\n \n \n\nTreats permission, incentive, headcount, and tooling as design surfaces — none of them as fixed.\n\n \n\n \n \n\nMindset\n\n \n\nFirst‑principle thinking. Asks why a process exists before asking how to improve it. Most are vestigial; subtraction follows.\n\n \n\nSystems over people. When something fails, the first question is what should have caught it automatically — not who dropped the ball.\n\n \n\nBuilds before deliberates. Ships a prototype that surfaces the answer instead of running a meeting that argues about it.\n\n \n\nAsymmetrical bets. Every action is a bet. Reads the data on cost and expected value before spending an hour. Operates a portfolio, not a hunch.\n\n \n\nComfort with structural conflict. Companies are complex systems with intersecting interests; conflict isn't an event, it's the ambient condition. The CAO doesn't seek it, doesn't avoid it, isn't weighed down by it. They operate inside it.\n\n \n\nHigh‑bandwidth attention. Twenty dashboards open, cross‑domain signal flowing in all day. The work is ever‑changing because the field is ever‑changing. The trait that survives this isn't curiosity — it's being undisturbed by the volume.\n\n \n \n \n\n \n \n 08\n \n\n## KPIs that aren't theater\n\n## \n \n \n\nA new function survives its first year only if it can be measured. Pick the wrong KPIs and the role becomes the very theater this document warns against. The test: a good KPI measures value created, not work performed.\n\n \n \n \n\nTheater KPIs · avoid\n\n \n\n Hours of AI training delivered\n Prompts in the company library\n AI tools and agents deployed\n Workshops run\n Employee NPS on \"AI experience\"\n \n\n \n \n \n\nReal KPIs · adopt\n\n \n\n Revenue per employee\n Gross margin per employee\n Growth rate of revenue per employee\n Cost per dollar of revenue\n Decision latency\n \n\n \n \n\n \n Tier 1 — Value KPIsThe headline numbers the owner reports to their board.\n \n \n \n\nRevenue per employee\n\n \n\nRevenue divided by FTE. The single cleanest measure of whether each person is producing more value. The owner already tracks this; the CAO is the executive whose work shows up here.\n\n \n\nDirection: up. First movement in 6‑12 months; the order‑of‑magnitude shift takes 12‑24.\n\n \n 6‑24 mo\n \n \n \n \n\nGross margin per employee\n\n \n\nRevenue per employee net of cost to produce it. Captures the case where tooling spend rises while headcount holds — revenue per FTE might rise, but margin per FTE is the truer signal.\n\n \n\nDirection: up. The CFO's preferred number.\n\n \n 6‑12 mo\n \n \n \n \n\nGrowth rate of revenue per employee\n\n \n\nYear‑over‑year acceleration in the headline number. The 5x‑a‑year claim from this document, measured directly. A growth rate, not a level.\n\n \n\nDirection: up sharply. Sustained linear growth across multiple quarters means the role is failing.\n\n \n 12‑24 mo\n \n\n Tier 2 — Velocity & costHow the value moved — through faster cycles or lower cost.\n \n \n \n\nCost per dollar of revenue\n\n \n\nTotal fully‑loaded cost — people, tools, vendors — divided by revenue. The operating ratio the CFO will fight over.\n\n \n\nDirection: down. Falls faster than headcount, because revenue rises while headcount holds.\n\n \n 6‑12 mo\n \n \n \n \n\nDecision latency\n\n \n\nElapsed time from \"decision needed\" to \"decision made\" on tracked operational decisions. Slow cycles cap revenue growth. Supporting evidence: approval‑layer depth.\n\n \n\nDirection: down. Falls measurably within two quarters if permission architecture is working.\n\n \n 3‑6 mo\n \n\n Tier 3 — Leading indicatorsWhat moves first and predicts the value movement that follows.\n \n \n \n\nAgency‑weighted hires\n\n \n\nPercentage of new hires where agency‑dimension scores outweighed tenure‑years in the final decision. The earliest signal that the input pipeline is changing.\n\n \n\nDirection: up. Direct measure of whether the hiring change is real or cosmetic.\n\n \n 3‑12 mo\n \n \n \n \n\nTenure‑to‑impact correlation\n\n \n\nCorrelation between years‑at‑company and shipped value. The deep cultural signal — when this weakens, the value KPIs compound.\n\n \n\nDirection: weakens. When agency drives value, the curve flattens.\n\n \n 18‑36 mo\n \n \n\n \n\nThese metrics aren't new. What's new is their weight — in the AI‑native era, they decide who wins. And right now, no executive has the focus, the tools, and the mindset to push them. The CAO is the executive who does.\n\n \n\n \n \n 09\n \n\n## Whose budget this eats\n\n## \n \n \n\nA new C‑suite function only exists when it has territory. Here is where the territory comes from — with rough numbers, because vague claims are how new roles get strangled in their first year. IBM's 2026 CEO study found companies that rewired five areas at once — technology, finance, HR, operations, cross‑functional collaboration — were 4x more likely to meet their AI objectives than those that didn't. The CAO is the executive whose mandate spans those five.\n\n \n \n \n HR / People Ops\n \n ~20%\n \n \n\nThe hiring methodology slice — filters, performance review structure, calibration. Comp admin, benefits, compliance stay with HR.\n\n \n \n \n L & D\n \n ~60%\n \n \n\nMost AI‑era expertise gets acquired on real projects, prototypes, and live processes — not in scheduled training. The 40% that remains is genuine domain skill‑building.\n\n \n \n \n IT / tooling\n \n 20‑80%\n \n \n\nDepends on what kind of company you are. If your main product is software, IT spend is product spend — the CAO eats only the slice that enables everyone else (~20%). If your main product is anything else — services, manufacturing, biotech, finance, consulting — IT is overhead and almost all of it becomes CAO territory (~80%).\n\n \n \n \n Middle management\n \n ~90%\n \n \n\nThe coordination overhead — meetings, status updates, cross‑team alignment — either automated or eliminated. Not the headcount: the function. Some managers transform into IC operators, some become CAO direct reports, the rest the company outgrows.\n\n \n \n\nEach of these functions will fight to keep what it has. None of them can lead the work that takes it — no function restructures itself out of existence. Without an executive whose mandate sits above all four, this work doesn't happen. The CAO is that executive.\n\n \n \n\n \n \n 10\n \n\n## Six hard questions\n\n## \n \n \n\nThe six objections this idea will face from a skeptical owner, board member, or existing C‑suite. Each one is real. None of them survive contact.\n\n \n \n \n\n01Is this a technologist or a people leader? I can't tell which one to hire.\n\n \n\nNeither, and both. The role isn't a technologist who happens to care about people; it's not a people leader who happens to use AI. It's a third shape — an executive whose primary tools are technical (agent pipelines, observability, evals, verification automation) and whose primary work product is structural (removing what stops people from producing more). The mindset to watch for: not controlling, pushing. Most C-suite roles control something — spend, headcount, operations, hiring. The CAO pushes — pushes the ceiling of what's possible, pushes the floor of what's stopping. If your candidate sounds like a governance officer, wrong shape.\n\n \n \n \n\n02Agency can't be measured. This is pseudoscience dressed up in psychometrics.\n\n \n\nThe same objection was made about intelligence in 1905, leadership in 1950, and emotional intelligence in 1995. Each one resolved the same way: imperfect measurement that's better than no measurement. More importantly, the CAO doesn't lean on one instrument. The ten dimensions are one input; revenue per employee is another; decision latency is another. Every action is a data‑backed bet, triangulated across measurements. The alternative — \"we can't measure agency so we'll keep hiring on tenure‑years\" — is what got the company to the problem in the first place. And if the agency dimensions still feel soft, evaluate the CAO on the value KPIs alone — revenue per employee, cost per dollar of revenue, decision latency. Those numbers don't depend on psychometrics.\n\n \n \n \n\n03If agency is so valuable, why doesn't the market already price it?\n\n \n\nIt does, badly. The market currently prices agency through founder equity and senior IC comp at frontier labs, which is why both compound so fast. In the broader enterprise market, 76% of large organizations now have a Chief AI Officer — up from 26% a year earlier (IBM IBV 2026). The market is hiring aggressively for the wrong shape. MIT Sloan and CIO Magazine independently predict the CAIO role will be absorbed back into existing functions within a few years as the technology matures. Supply for the right shape is small — most candidates already sit in high‑comp seats. By 2028, supply catches up through internal promotion and career pivots. The first companies to hire CAOs — who are also rare, also underpriced — will get them at a discount, and have years to build pipelines for the agency‑first technical talent the CAO attracts. The companies chasing in 2028 will pay three times the comp to attract half the quality — that's the arbitrage window, and it closes once the market catches on.\n\n \n \n \n\n04You're describing a consultant engagement, not a permanent C‑suite role.\n\n \n\nA consultant can audit your approval layers and recommend changes. They can't operate the systems that make this work — the observability layer, the agent pipelines, the evals catching AI errors in real time, the verification automation woven into legal and analytics and brand. They can't run a 24‑month series of data‑backed bets on which obstacle to remove next, watch the metrics, learn, redirect. They can't push limits — they recommend boundaries. The CAO is the executive whose job is to operate the system, not deliver findings about it. Consultants leave; the running system has to keep running.\n\n \n \n \n\n05AI is the system. Why do I need an executive for what runs itself?\n\n \n\nToday's systems don't run themselves yet — someone has to operate them. But that's the smaller answer. The deeper one: even when systems run more autonomously, someone has to decide which systems to build, which limits to push, which obstacles to attack first. Those are strategic calls, not technical ones. The CAO doesn't push the buttons. The CAO decides which buttons should exist.\n\n \n \n \n\n06How do I know this is working in year one?\n\n \n\nMost value KPIs take 12‑24 months. But three indicators move in year one and tell you whether the hire was right. Decision latency falls within two quarters — measurable. Agency‑weighted hires shows up in every hiring loop within 90 days. And the CAO themselves should be surfacing the evidence — that's part of the role. By month six, you should have a dashboard showing which obstacles were attacked, which moved, and which didn't. The qualitative test: are the company's top‑quartile people pushing for more responsibility, or quietly looking around? The CAO's first year is whether the floor moves. The ceiling moves in year two.\n\n \n \n \n\n \n \n 11\n \n\n## The price of ignoring this\n\n## \n \n \n\nYou won't see this in your KPI dashboard first. You'll see it in the competitor your sales team keeps losing deals to — the one with 1/5 the headcount.\n\n \n \n Year 1\n \n \n\nYou notice the 1/5‑team competitor.\n\n \n\nThey're smaller, regional, easy to dismiss. But their revenue per employee is already 3x yours, and they're hiring faster. Your numbers haven't moved. The market's have. You'll attribute it to their stage, their luck, their niche — anything except the structural difference.\n\n \n \n \n Year 2\n \n \n\nThey're selling to your customers.\n\n \n\nPricing 30‑40% below yours and still profitable — because their cost per dollar of revenue is half. Your CFO blames the vendors. The real problem is that no one in your company operates the systems that would close the gap. You buy more tools; they pull more customers.\n\n \n \n \n Year 3\n \n \n\nThey're your size now.\n\n \n\nGrowing 3x faster, half the headcount, your best people on their team. Even if you hire a CAO today, the four functions that should have been compressed have hardened into structure. Your remaining team has been selected for compliance, not push. The restructure isn't expensive anymore — it's politically impossible.\n\n \n \n \n\n \n\nThe cost of hiring a Chief Agency Officer is one salary. The cost of not hiring one is the company.\n\n \n\n \n \n 12\n \n\n## Where to start today\n\n## \n \n\n \n \n 01\n \n \n\nHow to talk to your exec team\n\n \n\nA short brief to share before the conversation. What lands, what triggers defensiveness, the questions to expect from your COO, CFO, and Head of People.\n\n \n \n DocRead →\n MCPInstall →\n \n \n \n 02\n \n \n\nAdopt the toolkit without the title\n\n \n\nFor companies not ready to hire. Use the ten dimensions in your hiring rubric. Use the theater‑vs‑real KPIs in your quarterly review. Give your COO the \"remove friction\" mandate as a side role. Same instruments, lower political cost. When the toolkit hits its ceiling, the hire becomes obvious.\n\n \n \n DocRead →\n MCPInstall →\n \n \n \n 03\n \n \n\nHiring a Chief Agency Officer\n\n \n\nSkillset map vs a Chief AI Officer, JD template, comp band by company stage, interview scorecard, first‑90‑day mandate.\n\n \n \n DocRead →\n MCPInstall →\n \n \n \n 04\n \n \n\nHiring agency‑first people\n\n \n\nSurgical adjustments to your existing hiring process — JD calibration, screening filter, rubric augmentation, question bank, calibration sessions. The CAO is one hire; this affects the next fifty.\n\n \n \n DocRead →\n MCPInstall →\n \n \n \n\n \n\n### Still not sure? Talk to the article.\n\n### \n \n\nAsk anything that's still unclear, anything you'd want to push on before you'd act on this, anything specific to your company that the document didn't cover. Private to this session.\n\n \n \n \n\nPick a question below or write your own.\n\n \n \n First 90 days at 200 people\n Real interview question for agency\n 30 vs 2000 person company\n Who should I hire?\n Apply to my industry\n \n \n \n Ask\n \n \n \n \n\n \n \n\nUpdated May 2026, by Oren Levitin\n\n \n\nIf any of this stuck, agreed, disagreed, or sparked a thought — drop me a line. I read everything.";

export const KPI_TRACKER_TEMPLATE: string = "KPI baseline & target\nFill in today's numbers. Set targets for month 6. Review monthly.\nMetric\nBaseline (today)\nTarget (month 6)\nTier 1 — Value\nRevenue per employee\nTotal revenue ÷ FTE. The headline.\n \n \nGross margin per employee\nGross margin ÷ FTE. Strips out scale.\n \n \nGrowth rate of revenue per employee\nYear-over-year % change. Should be increasing.\n \n \nTier 2 — Velocity & cost\nCost per dollar of revenue\nTotal operating cost ÷ revenue. Includes AI tooling.\n \n \nDecision latency\nMedian days, top 20 recurring decisions.\n \n \nTier 3 — Leading indicators\nAgency-weighted hires\n% of new hires scoring high on initiative, verification, taste, feedback metabolism.\n \n \nTenure-to-impact correlation\nCorrelation coefficient. Target: zero or negative.\n \n \nNotes\n \n \n";
